    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "72289851_44107889",
        "filename": "client/crashpad_client_win.cc",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 350,
      "author": {
        "id": 1149139
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-12-03T15:31:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "My initial thoughts was all this checking for loader lock would be for debugging purposes only as it\u0027s still relying on undocumented behavior and so didn\u0027t want something to unexpectedly break in production code (say due to third party code interactions). I guess as we\u0027re doing a test in all cases it should be safe to enable as a CHECK and we\u0027d quickly see if it starts hitting in places in production we didn\u0027t expect.",
      "parentUuid": "eba20c35_6aedab29",
      "revId": "11f748b78f9200d3e5cdd96b90c5d7704851a6bd",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "63a4f5d3_5614cf6b",
        "filename": "util/BUILD.gn",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 746,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2019-12-03T05:09:18Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "1. We’d normally prefix the name with the main test name because the “out” directory doesn’t provide any other form of namespacing, and especially in a large Chrome build, it’s nice to have some kind of attribution for these sorts of things. See the two targets immediately above. So, crashpad_util_test_loader_lock_test_dll or something. Maybe even leave off the trailing _dll, because it‘ll already be part of the filename.\n\n2. We already have a test-only target named loader_lock_dll in handler. I know it violates the rule I just gave you. Having two similar targets is confusing, but I guess the namespace prefix I suggested would resolve that.",
      "revId": "11f748b78f9200d3e5cdd96b90c5d7704851a6bd",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
